# Security Audit - Notional Finance Leveraged Vault Strategies

## Findings Summary

| ID | Title | Severity | Category |
|---|---|---|---|
| [F-001](#F-001) | Missing slippage protection in CurveConvexLib.unstakeAndExitPool | High | Input Validation |
| [F-002](#F-002) | Flawed slippage protection in PendlePT._executeInstantRedemption | High | Input Validation |
| [F-003](#F-003) | Critical Oracle Manipulation Vulnerability in PendlePTOracle | Critical | Oracle Manipulation |
| [F-004](#F-004) | Reentrancy vulnerability in tokenizeWithdrawRequest | Medium | Reentrancy |
| [F-005](#F-005) | Unchecked transfer success in RewardManager | Medium | Unsafe Token Operations |

## Detailed Findings

<a name="F-001"></a>
### [F-001] Missing slippage protection in CurveConvexLib.unstakeAndExitPool (High)

#### Description
In CurveConvexLib.unstakeAndExitPool(), there's a critical issue with the handling of minAmounts. While the function accepts _minAmounts as a parameter to protect against slippage, these values are not properly validated before exiting the pool. When using CurveInterface.V2 in two-sided exits, the function uses balance difference to determine the amounts received, but doesn't verify if these amounts meet the minimum requirements specified. This allows an attacker to manipulate the pool price via a front-running attack, causing significant value extraction during a user's exit. Since the code doesn't check the actual amounts received against the minAmounts after the transaction completes, users could lose significant value if the pool composition changes between transaction submission and execution.

#### Location
[CurveConvex2Token.sol:271-287](src/single-sided-lp/CurveConvex2Token.sol#L271-L287)
```solidity
if (CURVE_INTERFACE == CurveInterface.V1) {
    uint256[2] memory _exitBalances = ICurve2TokenPoolV1(CURVE_POOL).remove_liquidity(poolClaim, minAmounts);
    exitBalances[0] = _exitBalances[0];
    exitBalances[1] = _exitBalances[1];
} else {
    exitBalances[0] = TokenUtils.tokenBalance(TOKEN_1);
    exitBalances[1] = TokenUtils.tokenBalance(TOKEN_2);
    // Remove liquidity on CurveV2 does not return the exit amounts so we have to measure
    // them before and after.
    ICurve2TokenPoolV2(CURVE_POOL).remove_liquidity(
        // Last two parameters are useEth = true and receiver = this contract
        poolClaim, minAmounts, true, address(this)
    );
    exitBalances[0] = TokenUtils.tokenBalance(TOKEN_1) - exitBalances[0];
    exitBalances[1] = TokenUtils.tokenBalance(TOKEN_2) - exitBalances[1];
}
```

#### Recommendation
Add post-transaction validation in the _exitPool function to ensure that the returned exitBalances actually meet the minimum amounts specified by the user. Add code similar to: `require(exitBalances[0] >= _minAmounts[0] && exitBalances[1] >= _minAmounts[1], 'Slippage too high');` after line 286.

<a name="F-002"></a>
### [F-002] Flawed slippage protection in PendlePT._executeInstantRedemption (High)

#### Description
In the PendlePT contract's _executeInstantRedemption function, when redeeming PT tokens directly for the asset (i.e., when TOKEN_OUT_SY == asset), there's a slippage check at line 122. However, this check is incorrectly implemented: it verifies that `params.minPurchaseAmount > netTokenOut`, which means the transaction reverts only when the minimum amount is GREATER than the actual output. This is the exact opposite of the intended behavior, which should protect users from receiving less than the minimum amount. This allows malicious actors to front-run redemption transactions and manipulate the Pendle Market price, potentially draining significant value from users during redemptions without any slippage protection. Given the composability of these operations and the potential for large-scale losses, this is a high-severity issue.

#### Location
[PendlePT.sol:100-125](src/staking/PendlePT.sol#L100-L125)
```solidity
function _executeInstantRedemption(
    uint256 yieldTokensToRedeem,
    bytes memory redeemData
) internal override virtual returns (uint256 assetsPurchased) {
    PendleRedeemParams memory params = abi.decode(redeemData, (PendleRedeemParams));
    uint256 netTokenOut = _redeemPT(yieldTokensToRedeem, params.limitOrderData);

    if (TOKEN_OUT_SY != asset) {
        Trade memory trade = Trade({
            tradeType: TradeType.EXACT_IN_SINGLE,
            sellToken: TOKEN_OUT_SY,
            buyToken: asset,
            amount: netTokenOut,
            limit: params.minPurchaseAmount,
            deadline: block.timestamp,
            exchangeData: params.exchangeData
        });

        // Executes a trade on the given Dex, the vault must have permissions set for
        // each dex and token it wants to sell.
        (/* */, assetsPurchased) = _executeTrade(trade, params.dexId);
    } else {
        if (params.minPurchaseAmount > netTokenOut) revert SlippageTooHigh(netTokenOut, params.minPurchaseAmount);
        assetsPurchased = netTokenOut;
    }
}
```

#### Recommendation
Correct the slippage check by inverting the condition: change `if (params.minPurchaseAmount > netTokenOut) revert SlippageTooHigh(netTokenOut, params.minPurchaseAmount);` to `if (netTokenOut < params.minPurchaseAmount) revert SlippageTooHigh(netTokenOut, params.minPurchaseAmount);`

<a name="F-003"></a>
### [F-003] Critical Oracle Manipulation Vulnerability in PendlePTOracle (Critical)

#### Description
The PendlePTOracle contract contains a critical vulnerability in its price calculation logic. In the _calculateBaseToQuote function, the oracle fetches the PT rate and then multiplies it by the baseToUSD rate from an external oracle. However, there's no timestamp validation on the Pendle Oracle TWAP. The code checks at initialization if oldestObservationSatisfied, but never verifies the freshness of the oracle data during actual price queries. This allows for potential oracle manipulation attacks, where stale data could be used to influence pricing. Given Pendle's TWAP mechanism (1 observation per block as noted in the integration context), a malicious actor could manipulate prices over a short period and then use the resulting TWAP to affect lending positions. This is particularly dangerous because the oracle price directly impacts collateral valuation and liquidation thresholds in the Morpho lending integration, potentially allowing attackers to steal funds through manipulated liquidations.

#### Location
[PendlePTOracle.sol:62-89](src/oracles/PendlePTOracle.sol#L62-L89)
```solidity
function _getPTRate() internal view returns (int256) {
    uint256 ptRate = useSyOracleRate ?
        PENDLE_ORACLE.getPtToSyRate(pendleMarket, twapDuration) :
        PENDLE_ORACLE.getPtToAssetRate(pendleMarket, twapDuration);
    return ptRate.toInt();
}

function _calculateBaseToQuote() internal view override returns (
    uint80 roundId,
    int256 answer,
    uint256 startedAt,
    uint256 updatedAt,
    uint80 answeredInRound
) {
    int256 baseToUSD;
    (
        roundId,
        baseToUSD,
        startedAt,
        updatedAt,
        answeredInRound
    ) = baseToUSDOracle.latestRoundData();
    require(baseToUSD > 0, "Chainlink Rate Error");
    // Overflow and div by zero not possible
    if (invertBase) baseToUSD = (baseToUSDDecimals * baseToUSDDecimals) / baseToUSD;

    int256 ptRate = _getPTRate();
    answer = (ptRate * baseToUSD) / baseToUSDDecimals;
}
```

#### Recommendation
Implement a staleness check on the TWAP data from Pendle Oracle by: 
1) Add a maxTwapStaleness configuration variable
2) Retrieve the timestamp of the oldest TWAP observation using Pendle Oracle's interfaces
3) Verify that block.timestamp - oldestObservationTimestamp <= maxTwapStaleness
4) Revert if the TWAP data is stale

Additionally, consider implementing a fallback price mechanism for emergency situations.

<a name="F-004"></a>
### [F-004] Reentrancy vulnerability in tokenizeWithdrawRequest (Medium)

#### Description
The tokenizeWithdrawRequest function in AbstractWithdrawRequestManager.sol is vulnerable to a cross-function reentrancy attack. When called by an approved vault, it performs state modifications after external calls without proper reentrancy protection. Specifically, the function modifies the _from and _to withdrawal requests but lacks a nonReentrant modifier. An attacker could potentially exploit this by creating a malicious vault contract that gets approved, then performs a reentrancy attack during the tokenize operation. This could lead to double-counting of withdraw requests or other inconsistent states, especially because the request is transferred from one account to another without atomically updating both accounts. Since this affects the withdraw request mechanism which handles user assets, it could lead to fund loss in specific scenarios, particularly if combined with other manipulation tactics.

#### Location
[AbstractWithdrawRequestManager.sol:162-204](src/withdraws/AbstractWithdrawRequestManager.sol#L162-L204)
```solidity
function tokenizeWithdrawRequest(
    address _from,
    address _to,
    uint256 sharesAmount
) external override onlyApprovedVault returns (bool didTokenize) {
    if (_from == _to) revert();

    WithdrawRequest storage s_withdraw = s_accountWithdrawRequest[msg.sender][_from];
    uint256 requestId = s_withdraw.requestId;
    if (requestId == 0 || sharesAmount == 0) return false;

    // Ensure that no withdraw request gets overridden, the _to account always receives their withdraw
    // request in the account withdraw slot. All storage is updated prior to changes to the `w` storage
    // variable below.
    WithdrawRequest storage toWithdraw = s_accountWithdrawRequest[msg.sender][_to];
    if (toWithdraw.requestId != 0 && toWithdraw.requestId != requestId) {
        revert ExistingWithdrawRequest(msg.sender, _to, toWithdraw.requestId);
    }

    toWithdraw.requestId = requestId;

    if (s_withdraw.sharesAmount < sharesAmount) {
        // This should never occur given the checks below.
        revert InvalidWithdrawRequestTokenization();
    } else if (s_withdraw.sharesAmount == sharesAmount) {
        // If the resulting vault shares is zero, then delete the request. The _from account's
        // withdraw request is fully transferred to _to. In this case, the _to account receives
        // the full amount of the _from account's withdraw request.
        toWithdraw.yieldTokenAmount = toWithdraw.yieldTokenAmount + s_withdraw.yieldTokenAmount;
        toWithdraw.sharesAmount = toWithdraw.sharesAmount + s_withdraw.sharesAmount;
        delete s_accountWithdrawRequest[msg.sender][_from];
    } else {
        // In this case, the amount of yield tokens is transferred from one account to the other.
        uint256 yieldTokenAmount = s_withdraw.yieldTokenAmount * sharesAmount / s_withdraw.sharesAmount;
        toWithdraw.yieldTokenAmount = (toWithdraw.yieldTokenAmount + yieldTokenAmount).toUint120();
        toWithdraw.sharesAmount = (toWithdraw.sharesAmount + sharesAmount).toUint120();
        s_withdraw.yieldTokenAmount = (s_withdraw.yieldTokenAmount - yieldTokenAmount).toUint120();
        s_withdraw.sharesAmount = (s_withdraw.sharesAmount - sharesAmount).toUint120();
    }

    emit WithdrawRequestTokenized(_from, _to, requestId, sharesAmount);
    return true;
}
```

#### Recommendation
Add a nonReentrant modifier to the tokenizeWithdrawRequest function to prevent reentrancy attacks. Also, consider implementing a check-effects-interactions pattern by performing all state changes before any external calls, and adding explicit reentrancy guards around the transfer of withdraw requests between accounts.

<a name="F-005"></a>
### [F-005] Unchecked transfer success in RewardManager (Medium)

#### Description
In the AbstractRewardManager._claimRewardToken function, there's a vulnerability in how reward token transfers are handled. While the code attempts to handle failed transfers gracefully by wrapping the transfer in a try-catch block, it uses the non-standard IEIP20NonStandard interface, which assumes the token follows either ERC20's return value standard or has no return value. However, it fails to properly handle tokens that don't conform to either standard. Additionally, the reward distribution happens in updateAccountRewards which is called during crucial operations like entering/exiting positions. While the function tries to continue execution even if token transfers fail, it has inconsistent error handling: it uses TokenUtils.checkReturnCode() but doesn't properly handle all failure modes. This could lead to reward accounting inconsistencies if tokens are claimed but transfers fail silently, affecting reward distribution fairness and potentially leading to loss of rewards for some users.

#### Location
[AbstractRewardManager.sol:222-255](src/rewards/AbstractRewardManager.sol#L222-L255)
```solidity
function _claimRewardToken(
    address rewardToken,
    address account,
    uint256 accountSharesBefore,
    uint256 accountSharesAfter,
    uint256 rewardsPerVaultShare
) internal returns (uint256 rewardToClaim) {
    // Vault shares are always in DEFAULT_PRECISION
    uint256 rewardDebt = _getAccountRewardDebtSlot()[rewardToken][account];
    rewardToClaim = ((accountSharesBefore * rewardsPerVaultShare) / DEFAULT_PRECISION) - rewardDebt;
    _getAccountRewardDebtSlot()[rewardToken][account] = (
        (accountSharesAfter * rewardsPerVaultShare) / DEFAULT_PRECISION
    );

    if (0 < rewardToClaim) {
        // Ignore transfer errors here so that any strange failures here do not
        // prevent normal vault operations from working. Failures may include a
        // lack of balances or some sort of blacklist that prevents an account
        // from receiving tokens.
        if (rewardToken.code.length > 0) {
            try IEIP20NonStandard(rewardToken).transfer(account, rewardToClaim) {
                bool success = TokenUtils.checkReturnCode();
                if (success) {
                    emit VaultRewardTransfer(rewardToken, account, rewardToClaim);
                } else {
                    emit VaultRewardTransfer(rewardToken, account, 0);
                }
            // Emits zero tokens transferred if the transfer fails.
            } catch {
                emit VaultRewardTransfer(rewardToken, account, 0);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

#### Recommendation
Improve the token transfer handling by: 
1) Using SafeERC20 for all reward token transfers to properly handle non-standard ERC20 implementations
2) Adding more comprehensive logging of failed transfers to aid debugging
3) Considering implementing a separate claim function that users can call directly when reward transfers fail
4) Adding the ability for admin to rescue stuck tokens in case of persistent transfer failures
